0","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Raleigh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Raleigh (House) in Pilton (Devon), recorded as <i>Radeleia</i> in 1086 and <i>Rawlegh</i> in 1535. The placename probably derives from Old English <i>rǣge</i> ‘roe deer’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: variant of   Riley  .","History: The English explorer Sir Walter Raleigh (1554–1618) was born in Hayes Barton, Devon, into a family of Devon gentry. He was related to most of the West Country's important families, including that of Sir Francis Drake. His half-brother was the explorer Sir Humphrey Gilbert. In 1578 Raleigh was granted a patent to explore and colonize “unknown lands” in America. In the 1580s he was granted extensive estates in Munster (Ireland), in reward for his suppression of the Desmond Rebellions."],"variants":[{"name":"Raley","meanings":["English: variant of   Raleigh  ."]},{"name":"Rawleigh","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Orlo.","English: variant of   Raleigh  , reflecting a common pronunciation."]},{"name":"Riley","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name chiefly from High Ryley in Accrington (Lancashire) and Riley in Kirkburton, which was in the manor of Wakefield (Yorkshire). In some cases the name may derive from Riley Farm in Eyam (Derbyshire), Royley in Royton (Lancashire), or Rylah in Scarcliffe (Derbyshire). The placenames all come from Old English <i>rȳge</i> ‘rye’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish: from <b>Ó Raghailligh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Raghailleach</i>’, Old Irish <i>Roghallach</i>. This is the name of a chieftain family in Cavan, related to the O'Rourkes. In Anglicized form it has also been confused with <b>Ó Raithile</b> found in Munster, usually Anglicized as <b>O'Rahilly</b> or   Rahilly  . See   O'Reilly  ."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":26,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Walter de Raleigh II was born about 1040, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Walter de Raleigh I, was 35 and his mother, Olga de Normandy, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Beatrice de Gand. He died on 14 October 1066, in Hastings, Sussex, England, at the age of 27."},"et":{"about 1040–14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"umbes 1040–14. oktoober 1066","1040–1066":"1040–1066","1040–1100":"1040–1100","1065–1101":"1065–1101","1006–Male":"1006–Surnud","1015–Female":"1015–Surnud","1006":"1006","about 1040":"umbes 1040","1015":"1015","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"14. oktoober 1066","1040":"1040","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Pilton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1040–14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"noin 1040–14. lokakuuta 1066","1040–1066":"1040–1066","1040–1100":"1040–1100","1065–1101":"1065–1101","1006–Male":"1006–Kuollut","1015–Female":"1015–Kuollut","1006":"1006","about 1040":"noin 1040","1015":"1015","1101":"1101","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"14. lokakuuta 1066","1040":"1040","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hastings, Sussex, England":"Hastings, Sussex, England","Pilton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Pilton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1040–14 October 1066, killed in the Battle of Hastings":"environ 1040–14 octobre 1066","1040–1066":"1040–1066","1040–1100":"1040–1100","1065–1101":"1065–1101","1006–Male":"1006–Décédé","1015–Female":"1015–Décédée","1006":"1006","about 1040":"environ 1040","1015":"1015","1101":"1101","1100":"110